    "narrative": "For today\u2019s slate, **Vinnie Pasquantino** headlines our offensive core with a massive 76.21 efficiency score. His matchup against Civale is a premier exploitation spot, boosted by a significant park factor and a favorable platoon dynamic that elevates his raw projection by nearly 20 points. Alongside him, **Seiya Suzuki** and **Corbin Carroll** are locked into the 67-point range; **Seiya Suzuki** benefits from a porous 5.19 xERA matchup against Buehler and a slow delivery that invites theft, while **Corbin Carroll** remains a top-tier asset due to his elite xwOBA and high-leverage spot in the order. **James Wood** rounds out our high-floor outfield, providing a dual threat of high-efficiency production and opportunistic baserunning against Holmes.\n\nThe margin between our starters and the bench remains razor-thin, evidenced by **Travis Bazzana** (50.78) being our most difficult exclusion. While **Travis Bazzana** carries a solid projection, he lacks the situational multipliers\u2014specifically the high-order batting slots and favorable platoon matchups\u2014that propelled **Dalton Rushing** and **Brice Turang** into the starting lineup. **Jose Caballero** fell significantly short of our floor at 39.32, largely due to the brutal matchup against deGrom, whose ability to neutralize basestealers makes **Jose Caballero** a liability in our SB-focused build today. \n\nWe are monitoring the **Mickey Moniak** situation closely; while his 57.42 score is respectable, he faces a daunting task against the 2.76 xERA of Burns. We are comfortable with this risk given the aggressive platoon ceiling he offers, but his proximity to the 50-point mark makes him the most volatile piece of our offensive puzzle. Across the board, we are prioritizing high-OPS environments and stolen base opportunities; if the wind shifts or late lineup changes shift **Dalton Rushing** or **James Wood** from their projected spots, we will pivot to maintain our efficiency targets.",
